Findings

High: src/App.jsx:83, src/App.jsx:313, and src/App.jsx:424 make App.jsx the app shell, auth/session manager, local persistence layer, progression engine, shop inventory manager, achievement sync point, and router all at once. That is the biggest maintainability risk in src, because almost every cross-cutting change now has to pass through one file.

High: src/pages/GamePage.jsx:60, src/pages/GamePage.jsx:269, src/pages/GamePage.jsx:311, and src/pages/GamePage.jsx:432 show that GamePage.jsx is really the game engine, not a page component. It owns round state, timers, powerups, feedback lifecycles, keyboard handling, and scoring. A new developer looking in features/game will still miss most of the real game logic because it lives in pages.

High: feature boundaries are inconsistent. Achievements are split across src/pages/ProfilePage.jsx:3, src/App.jsx:22, src/game/achievements, src/components/achievements, and src/styles/components/achievements.css; shop is split between src/pages/ShopPage.jsx:2, src/features/shop, and src/constants; auth is split between src/pages, src/components/auth, and src/services. That makes the codebase harder to navigate because related files do not share one obvious home.

Medium: terminology is inconsistent around “difficulty” vs “mode”. src/constants/difficultyConfig.js:1 defines DIFFICULTY_*, while src/App.jsx:8 and src/pages/GamePage.jsx:4 immediately alias those values back to “mode”. That is a signal the file and symbol names no longer match the product language.
Medium: there are misleading alias files and leftover structure. src/config/shopCatalog.js:1, src/features/game/gameConfig.js:1, src/features/game/gameUtils.js:1, and src/features/game/difficultyConfig.js:1 are pass-through modules, and src/styles/_deprecated.css:1 is intentionally unused. These files make the tree look richer than it is and slow down discovery.

Medium: styling is still organized as large global buckets instead of by feature ownership. src/main.jsx:5 imports one global stylesheet, and src/styles/app.css:3 fans out to broad files like game.css (1,372 lines), layout.css (774), and profile.css (560). That makes UI changes harder to trace from component to style source.

Medium: src/pages/ProfilePage.jsx:15, src/pages/ProfilePage.jsx:102, and src/pages/ProfilePage.jsx:146 combine domain calculations, small reusable subcomponents, achievement filtering, and the full page layout in one file. It is readable today, but it will become difficult to evolve once profile or achievements expand further.
Recommended Direction

Keep route files thin and rename pages to routes if you want that intent to be explicit. A route file should mostly compose feature screens and pass route-level params.
Move feature-owned code under feature roots. Example:
src/
  app/
    AppRoutes.jsx
    providers/
  features/
    auth/
    game/
    history/
    leaderboard/
    profile/
    shop/
  shared/
    components/
    hooks/
    lib/
    styles/
Rename src/constants/difficultyConfig.js to something like src/features/game/config/modes.js. The current code already speaks in “modes”, so the filesystem should match that language.
Move src/constants/shopCatalog.js to src/features/shop/catalog/items.js or src/features/shop/config/catalog.js. Shop data is feature data, not an app-wide constant.
Move src/game/achievements either into src/features/profile/achievements if achievements are primarily profile-facing, or into src/features/achievements if they will be used across multiple screens.
Move src/components/auth into src/features/auth/components, and keep LoginPage.jsx / SignupPage.jsx as thin route wrappers around LoginScreen / SignupScreen.
Oversized Files To Split

App.jsx: split into AppRoutes.jsx, useAuthSession.js, usePlayerProgress.js, useInventory.js, and useAchievementProgress.js. Reason: each area changes for different product reasons and should not share one edit surface.

GamePage.jsx: split into useGameSession.js, useRoundTimer.js, usePowerups.js, useClickFeedback.js, and a thin GameScreen.jsx. Reason: the page currently mixes engine logic, effect cleanup, and presentation wiring.

ProfilePage.jsx: extract profileStats.js, ProfileHero.jsx, RankShowcase.jsx, PlayerSummarySection.jsx, and ProfileAchievementsSection.jsx. Reason: it currently mixes derived data, reusable UI blocks, and one large render tree.

styles/components/game.css and styles/components/profile.css: split by component or subfeature, or co-locate per feature. Reason: developers should be able to jump from a component to its styles without scanning a 500-1,300 line stylesheet.
Naming Improvements

gameMath.js -> gameScoring.js and gamePositioning.js if kept separate; “math” is too vague.
historyUtils.js -> historyStats.js or historyEntries.js; it currently mixes entry creation and leaderboard derivation.
modeUtils.js -> modeHelpers.js or merge into the game feature once modes.js exists.
shopCatalog.js -> shopItems.js or catalog.js; “catalog” is fine, but pairing it with the feature path makes it clearer.
Assumption: this review is scoped to src only. I did not evaluate whether the backend structure in server should mirror these same feature boundaries.